of Rio de Janeiro," published

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:46.930
in 2013, "The Throws of
Democracy, Brazil since 1989,"

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:50.800
published in 2008, and "Hello,
Hello, Brazil, Popular Music

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:53.800
in the Making of Modern
Brazil," from 2004.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:55.740
He recently wrote
the introduction

00:01:55.740 --> 00:02:00.000
for a new English translation
of Vida Vertiginosa,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.050
Vertiginous Life,
by Joao do Rio,

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:05.720
who is a contemporary
of Lima Barreto.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:07.640
And foe probably.

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:10.340
The book was published this
year by New London Librarian

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:13.950
and the translation
by Ana Lessa-Schmidt.

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:16.150
And thank you for calling
our attention to that

00:02:16.150 --> 00:02:19.190
and we're getting on
it and all those books.

00:02:19.190 --> 00:02:24.270
I'm very excited to have
Lilia Moritz Schwarcz here

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:25.570
in the library.

00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:26.870
For me it's a great honor.

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:30.350
As a grad student both Bryan
and Lilia were both references,

00:02:30.350 --> 00:02:35.170
so for me it's truly amazing
to have them here today.

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:37.520
She wears many hats
in her different roles

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:39.470
as an intellectual,
writer, publisher,

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:42.760
mentor and overall
force of nature.

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:44.060
She's a full professor

00:02:44.060 --> 00:02:47.120
in the Faculdade de Filosofia
Letras e Ciencias Humanas

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:49.680
at the University of
Sao Paulo in Brazil.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:53.650
Where she also received her
PhD in social anthropology.

00:02:53.650 --> 00:02:57.520
Her main areas of research
are history of slaves,

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:01.960
racial theories, history of the
Brazilian empire, academic art

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.430
and history of anthropology.

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:09.490
She's the author, co-author
or editor of over 50 titles.

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:10.790
We have them here.

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:12.940
I search for them.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:15.850
Some of them are
outside you can see them.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:18.450
And they include Retrato
em branco e negro,

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:22.200
Portrait in White
and Black, from 1987,

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:25.440
A Longa Viagem da
Bibilioteca dos Reis from 2002,

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:28.880
The Long Journey of the King's
Library, O Sol do Brazil,

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:32.090
from 2008, The Son of
Brazil and the book

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:34.500
that brings us here
today, Triste Visionario,

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:37.530
Lima Barreto from 2017.

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:40.170
Three of her books are available
in English, so those of you

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:44.080
who cannot yet read
in Portuguese,

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:47.620
I welcome you to look them up.

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:51.100
Spectacle of Racist, Science
Institutions and Racial Theories

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:55.090
in Brazil at the end of the 19th
Century, The Emperor's Beard,

00:03:55.090 --> 00:03:59.560
Pedros II, A Tropical
King, from 2004.

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:02.140
And Brazil, A Biography
is coming

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:07.450
out next year I just learned,
so, that's very exciting.

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:08.790
Lilia has also been the curator

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:11.030
