&gt;&gt; Lilia Moritz Schwarcz:
Well, good afternoon.

00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:17.880
Thank you so much.

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:21.420
Thank you, Talia, for this
beautiful introduction

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:23.410
to my biography.

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:26.040
Don't pay attention to her.

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:27.920
It's not true.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:33.780
I just want to start thanking
this very honorable invitation

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:40.480
from the Hispanic Division
of the Library of Congress.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.940
I want to mention Talia
Guzman-Gonzales [assumed

00:06:43.940 --> 00:06:47.340
spelling] that took care
of really everything,

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:49.950
including my research today.

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:54.600
And also my colleague, Bryan
McCann, for the kindness

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:58.280
of being here to
discuss my presentation.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:03.440
I agreed with Talia that I
would talk about my last book,

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:08.040
Lima Barreto, Sad
Vision, [inaudible].

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:09.840
I thought it would
be good to start

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:13.250
with the title, "Sad Visionary."

00:07:13.250 --> 00:07:15.700
I wanted to put a
balance in the title.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:20.400
For example, if you think
about sad, sad is a word

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:24.070
that Lima Barreto uses a lot.

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:28.620
Sad is the title of
his most famous novel,

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:32.010
"Triste Fim de Policaropo
Quaresma," the Sad End

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:33.980
of Policaropo Quaresma."

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:40.340
But sad in popular Brazil, it
means a person that is stubborn.

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:41.900
It's persistent.

00:07:41.900 --> 00:07:43.300
That insists.

00:07:43.300 --> 00:07:47.580
So you can see that you have
an ambivalence in one word.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:50.740
Visionary, visionary
because, again,

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.070
Lima Barreto used
it a lot, this word.

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:54.370
Visionary.

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:58.500
Again, in Sad End of
Policaropo Quaresma,

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:02.390
there is a particular moment
when Floriano Peixoto,

00:08:02.390 --> 00:08:06.640
our former president and a
character, evil character

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.860
of Lima Barreto, says
to Policaropo Quaresma,

00:08:10.860 --> 00:08:14.240
"Policaropo, you
are a visionary.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:17.790
I can't trust you,
it's not a compliment."

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:20.690
He's trying to say, so,
visionary can be a person

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:24.710
that sees the future, but a
visionary can also be a person

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:27.210
that is a fool, kind of lunatic.

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:32.560
So, you can see what kind of
problems I had in my book.

00:08:32.560 --> 00:08:37.050
No, a biography is an
exercise of ambiguity.

00:08:37.050 --> 00:08:42.730
No? It's another exercise of
being affected, to be distant,

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:46.990
to be very very closed
at the same time.

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:50.150
Lima Barreto [inaudible]
said, "It's not" --

00:08:50.150 --> 00:08:52.760
it's a very well known
author in brazil,

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:57.100
a very well known writer,
and it was very well said it.

00:08:57.100 --> 00:09:00.590
So, what I tried to do and
I tried to explain to you

00:09:00.590 --> 00:09:06.410
in this afternoon, I tried
to come up with new questions

00:09:06.410 --> 00:09:08.360
for the same character.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:13.200
Questions that I think it's a
kind of thing of my generation,

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:17.270
my generation that we are
dealing with civil rights,

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:18.720
problems of civil rights.

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:23.530
So I asked Lima Barreto
about race, gender,

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.880
region and generation.

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:30.810
All social markers of difference
that I tried to put together

00:09:30.810 --> 00:09:32.790
in a kind of intersection.

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:34.480
Let's see if I will succeed, no?

00:09:34.480 --> 00:09:43.410
So, let me start
quoting Lima Barreto.

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:46.100
So, this is Lima
Barreto, "The republic

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.900
of Brazil was the
regime of corruption.

00:09:48.900 --> 00:09:54.630
Nobody wants to debate,
nobody wants to stir up ideas.

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:58.380
Nobody wants to put any
real feeling into it.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:01.880
Everybody wants a
slice of the action.

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:05.020
The jurists want their slice,

00:10:05.020 --> 00:10:07.840
the philosophers
want their slice,

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:13.170
the doctor want their slice,
the novelists want their slice,

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:15.440
the engineerings
want their slice,

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:20.510
the journalists want their
slice, Brazil is one big apple.

00:10:20.510 --> 00:10:22.100
All brazil, [speaking
foreign language]."

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:27.510
Let me try just a test on you.

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:30.610
The body and the style
are very present day,

00:10:30.610 --> 00:10:32.580
in Brazil and also here.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:36.840
But the piece itself it's
almost a 100 years old.

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:42.120
However current it may seem,
it was actually published --

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:47.570
let me just move --
published in 1918

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:53.180
in an [inaudible] magazine
called A.B.C. The title,

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:57.370
"A Political Publicana,
The Republican Politics,"

00:10:57.370 --> 00:11:02.010
had a very clear target and
was signed by a colonist

00:11:02.010 --> 00:11:04.760
of Brazil First Republic.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:08.170
Famous for his very
critical style.

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:09.470
We are talking about
[speaking foreign language].

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:14.280
Lima, to his friends,
[speaking foreign language]

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:20.790
to his readers, but
also, Jonathan, Aaron,

00:11:20.790 --> 00:11:22.270
[speaking foreign language],
that one, and [inaudible]

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:29.400
that barely conceal the
author's true identity.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:34.950
They were his nick names.

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:39.230
Pick names, as he liked to joke.

00:11:39.230 --> 00:11:40.530
Or [speaking foreign language].

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:44.860
Black by argent size,
and literature,

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:50.030
Lima Barreto brought black
antagonist into the foreground.

00:11:50.030 --> 00:11:55.690
He felt the same thing that
was his own subjectivity

00:11:55.690 --> 00:12:00.540
and was able to describe them
in color, sensitive terms.

00:12:00.540 --> 00:12:03.940
I'm going to quote
Lima Barreto once more.

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:10.750
"They were simple seamen, low
ranking officers, white, blacks,

00:12:10.750 --> 00:12:12.850
mulattos, [speaking
foreign language],

00:12:12.850 --> 00:12:16.590
people of every color
and disposition.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:21.130
Folks who had gotten themselves
mixed up in their adventure

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:26.900
out of the nasty habit of
doing what they are told.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:28.820
This is comes from
[speaking foreign language].

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:38.210
In [inaudible] context, Lima
was a near solitary combatant

00:12:38.210 --> 00:12:40.540
against racism in Brazil.

00:12:40.540 --> 00:12:45.030
Against race [inaudible], that
was a big fashion in Brazil.

00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:46.870
I quote him once more.

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:50.950
"A white man intellectual,"
he would say,

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:54.740
"is measured [inaudible],
a black man, [inaudible]."

00:12:54.740 --> 00:13:03.490
In his novels, chronicles,
short stories, diaries,

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:07.400
Lima Barreto denounced the
discrimination he suffered,

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:12.030
that's of racist he
endured, great or small

00:13:12.030 --> 00:13:16.720
and in the sense his
literature was solidary,

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:21.060
as he would say, militant.

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:27.110
Freedom was a concept dear to
Lima Barreto, who from a line

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:30.050
of slaves on both sides.

00:13:30.050 --> 00:13:31.540
His grandfather,

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:36.210
Manuel Feliciano [speaking
foreign language] had actually

00:13:36.210 --> 00:13:41.670
owned his grandmother and never
recognized the relationship,

00:13:41.670 --> 00:13:45.780
as it was all too common
in Brazilian history

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:52.080
of which we only know one
side, the maternal side.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:54.670
His father, [speaking foreign
language] was a type setter

00:13:54.670 --> 00:13:58.510
during the Brazilian empire
and the proud inventor

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:01.820
of a special phones
created especially

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:04.660
for the printing
of the layout in.

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:06.120
The golden law.

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:11.210
The empire's most popular
and indeed less law.

00:14:11.210 --> 00:14:20.710
As the republic we'll begin in
1989 and the layout was in 1888.

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:24.620
Lima's mother, -- oh,
this is the golden law.

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:29.320
Lima's mother, Dona Amalia,
was a granddaughter of slaves.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:34.100
She trained as a teacher
and became head mistress

00:14:34.100 --> 00:14:35.960
of the Sintahoza
[phonetic spelling] school

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:39.230
for girls in Laranjeiras.

00:14:39.230 --> 00:14:41.210
The Barretos therefore belonged

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:43.830
to those African Brazilian
families who believed

00:14:43.830 --> 00:14:47.740
that true freedom would
come to education,

00:14:47.740 --> 00:14:50.790
not with a cold letter
of the law.

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:54.980
On the fridge of the system
there was no room for such forms

00:14:54.980 --> 00:14:59.170
of social mobility, even
if they steal the pendant

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:00.970
on a certain kind of patronage.

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:03.540
And that was what happened

00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:06.690
in the two sides of
Barreto's family.

00:15:06.690 --> 00:15:10.070
Both having perfections
and social alliance

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:11.840
with powerful families

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:16.670
of [inaudible] Province
and later state.

00:15:16.670 --> 00:15:19.860
Laranjeiras, as you can
see is the neighborhood

00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:21.450
where the Barretos would live.

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:27.270
And it was then a highly
diversified neighborhood,

00:15:27.270 --> 00:15:31.600
socially speaking, as can be
seen from the architecture

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:34.430
and the people in this photo.

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:39.160
However, fate would not
be kind to the family.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:43.850
Dona Amalia died from
tuberculosis in 1887,

00:15:43.850 --> 00:15:46.900
leaving her widower,
Joao Henriques

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:49.200
to raise the three kids alone.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.970
Even so, Joao Henriques
didn't neglect his

00:15:54.970 --> 00:15:56.450
children's education.

00:15:56.450 --> 00:16:00.270
On the day of the golden law,
there he was with his son

00:16:00.270 --> 00:16:04.210
at his side, turned out to
watch the pomp and the ceremony.

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:09.500
It was an event that Lima would
rewrite on many occasions.

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:15.880
On one of these he recalled
how Miss Theresa, his teacher,

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:18.040
came into the class and declared

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:21.120
that there were no
more slaves in Brazil.

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:27.250
Still only a boy, Lima got
the wrong end of the stick.

00:16:27.250 --> 00:16:33.540
He arrived home and informed
his father that from that day

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:39.210
on he could no longer
ground him.

00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:44.080
[speaking foreign language].

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:49.880
The future would not be rosy
for Lima and his family.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:52.370
[speaking foreign language]
the godson of Ouro Preto,

00:16:52.370 --> 00:16:56.550
the cabinet chief of the
last imperial government,

00:16:56.550 --> 00:17:00.290
fell along with his
protector, becoming one

00:17:00.290 --> 00:17:04.820
of the first unemployed
of the second Reich.

00:17:04.820 --> 00:17:09.710
Even so, he managed to
find an administrative post

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:13.620
at a mad house on
Ilna do Governador.

00:17:13.620 --> 00:17:15.550
That's the house.

00:17:15.550 --> 00:17:18.400
That's the house nowadays.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:23.990
Madness, real and social,
social and real, became a fixer

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:27.570
to Lima Barreto's life
from that point on.

00:17:27.570 --> 00:17:29.320
And he would never shrink

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:35.400
from criticizing the mad house
system was, as he often claimed,

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:38.480
a micro cause of wider society.

00:17:38.480 --> 00:17:41.810
Shot through with the
same social, political

00:17:41.810 --> 00:17:44.130
and racial differences.

00:17:44.130 --> 00:17:47.130
At asylum he would say often,

00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:51.220
"Black was always the
harshest culture."

00:17:51.220 --> 00:17:56.710
"The asylum," he wrote, "was
a place for invisibility."

00:17:56.710 --> 00:18:00.110
Black invisibility.

00:18:00.110 --> 00:18:05.400
Lima Barreto studied in
good schools from this --

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:07.360
as this one in Niteroi.

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:12.990
Fulfilled his father's dream, he
was accepted in the Politecnica.

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:15.720
The engineering program.

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.530
Where he claimed
where he suffered

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:21.570
for the first time
discrimination.

00:18:21.570 --> 00:18:23.830
This is Politecnica.

00:18:23.830 --> 00:18:29.390
This is a very rare photography
of the Lima Barreto group.

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:32.380
Lima Barreto is there
on the right side

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:34.960
and you can see him here.

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:41.290
Yeah. In this time torn photo
we see Lima wearing a large tie

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:46.050
and a borrowed jacket
looking into the future.

00:18:46.050 --> 00:18:50.010
He who claimed not to belong
to this select chick group,

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:56.770
with this European style elite
that refused to accept him.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:19:01.050
Unfortunately, Lima would have
no time to finish the course.

00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:05.090
In 1902 having failed
to balance the books

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:09.930
on [speaking foreign language],
Joao Henriques, Lima's father,

00:19:09.930 --> 00:19:12.730
was forced into retirement.

00:19:12.730 --> 00:19:19.050
The boy left the Politecnica and
entered public life as a clerk.

00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:22.800
With a war -- he was a
clerk in the war office,

00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:26.010
a place he always hated.

00:19:26.010 --> 00:19:32.130
What he really wanted was to
make a living from literature.

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:35.680
He wrote in his diary,
he wrote in his diary,

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:38.760
"I will marry literature."

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:42.730
The civil service struck
him as a waste of time.

00:19:42.730 --> 00:19:45.850
Marry a bread and butter job.

00:19:45.850 --> 00:19:49.650
I'm going to quote once
more, "We are all born

00:19:49.650 --> 00:19:55.220
to the civil service, that
[inaudible], no conflict

00:19:55.220 --> 00:19:57.290
or violent [inaudible],

00:19:57.290 --> 00:20:04.330
five hours of plain sailing
every day, [inaudible] for life.

00:20:04.330 --> 00:20:06.550
All of that sits perfectly well

00:20:06.550 --> 00:20:10.370
with our expectations
and temperament.

00:20:10.370 --> 00:20:16.410
In a day's work for the state
there is no unpredictability

00:20:16.410 --> 00:20:20.160
and replies, no extra
effort to get

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:22.770
up to [inaudible] to tomorrow.

00:20:22.770 --> 00:20:27.920
Everything precedes calmly and
smoothly, with no collisions,

00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:32.900
no surprise, as one goes
about drafting the same papers

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:35.610
and memorandums,
the same decrees

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:39.330
in the very same
fashion all year long.

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:44.440
Save for bank holidays,
holidays and optional holidays,

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:49.580
clearly one of the best
inventions of our republic."

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:52.440
So, he set about
reinventing himself.

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:57.580
He moves to Todos os
Santos, literally all saints,

00:20:57.580 --> 00:21:03.070
though he claimed the saints had
long since abandoned the place.

00:21:03.070 --> 00:21:08.670
At the same time from that
day on he was used to take --

00:21:08.670 --> 00:21:13.610
to take the central
station train every day.

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:16.010
That was an extended
huge generator

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:18.830
that includes the suburb.

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:25.270
In fact, Lima Barreto started to
write a literature in transit.

00:21:25.270 --> 00:21:29.580
In -- and he used to
-- but this is a line

00:21:29.580 --> 00:21:33.050
of the Central do Brazil
and you see Rio de Janeiro,

00:21:33.050 --> 00:21:37.470
that is the zero mark and then
Todos os Santos in the middle

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:42.500
and then this is a second
class car that he used to say,

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:49.480
"the second class car in the
morning is black, all black."

00:21:50.630 --> 00:21:55.330
Lima Barreto became
also a secretary

00:21:55.330 --> 00:21:59.940
with a very fashionable
magazine called Fon Fon.

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:03.570
Then promptly he resigned.

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:05.180
He used to say that he didn't'

00:22:05.180 --> 00:22:09.500
like having his copies
constantly being.

00:22:10.610 --> 00:22:15.910
But his real work, his real
challenge was literature.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:21.600
And in 1909 he had
already written two novels.

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:25.100
But he decided to start
with the "Recollections

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:27.660
of the Clerk, Isaias Caminha."

00:22:27.660 --> 00:22:31.660
That he found more aggressive.

00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:39.410
Lima had this kind of capacity
to make noise, a lot of noise.

00:22:39.410 --> 00:22:44.010
"Isaias Caminha" is the story
of a boy, the son of a priest

00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:47.670
and the slave mother,
who goes to the big city

00:22:47.670 --> 00:22:50.690
to make something of himself.

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:54.460
And runs up against prejudice.

00:22:54.460 --> 00:22:57.780
Skin changes, he wrote.

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:01.310
In the second part of
the book he picks a fight

00:23:01.310 --> 00:23:03.320
with the journalist,
[inaudible],

00:23:03.320 --> 00:23:07.770
when normally sitting,
Oh Global, the newspaper,

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:11.290
Oh Global, he attacks the
newspaper he wrote it for

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:13.560
and the colleagues
he worked with.

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:14.860
Including John [inaudible].

00:23:14.860 --> 00:23:20.750
He was immediately
blacklisted and had the doors

00:23:20.750 --> 00:23:25.130
of the big press
slammed to his face.

00:23:25.130 --> 00:23:29.900
But he, in his way, was
a stubborn person and set

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:33.490
up a magazine of
his own, Floreal.

00:23:33.490 --> 00:23:37.480
Which lasted only four issues,

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:42.660
and Lima thanked the
35 loyal subscribers

00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:46.270
who had stayed the course.

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:51.320
Lima fell in with a group
of friends who used to hang

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:53.780
out around the bars downtown.

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:57.660
And together they went by the
name of Confedia [inaudible].

00:23:57.660 --> 00:24:02.600
Con fraternity of clerks.

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:06.030
The group of drinking
buddies used to come together

00:24:06.030 --> 00:24:10.140
to exchange the user to say
useless theories and ideas.

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:15.340
They used it to be seen in
a particular bar called,

00:24:15.340 --> 00:24:18.510
"Bi Papagaiyou [assumed
spelling], the Parrots Bar.

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:22.780
Lima often mentioned that
even the Papagaiyou, the bird,

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:27.100
liked to drink a
lot and in this kind

00:24:27.100 --> 00:24:32.800
of situation the parrot used
it to blame against republic.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:37.560
I do not know if this is true
or this is Lima, but he's trying

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:40.150
to fictionalize his own life.

00:24:40.150 --> 00:24:44.250
But the thing is the
group like very much --

00:24:44.250 --> 00:24:49.930
the group was a kind of creating
a new kind of modernist,

00:24:49.930 --> 00:24:56.650
a new kind of way of seeing
Brazil, to transporting Brazil.

00:24:56.650 --> 00:25:04.610
But Lima Barreto he wrote,
"Nume e a Nympha" in 1911

00:25:04.610 --> 00:25:07.820
and attacked the politicians.

00:25:07.820 --> 00:25:12.720
And he wrote "Dr.
Bogoloff" in 1912,

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:14.530
when he attacked the Brazilians

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:16.800
and called the Brazilians
Botherrists.

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:20.130
He used to say that the
resilience loved just

00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:23.640
to import ideas and theories.

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:29.860
In 1914 Lima could
not hold out no longer

00:25:29.860 --> 00:25:32.630
and was committed
for the first time.

00:25:32.630 --> 00:25:36.840
He was found drunk and
his brother decided

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:39.790
to put him in the hospital.

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:44.030
There admittance office,
perhaps as a curtsey

00:25:44.030 --> 00:25:47.480
for one civil servant
to another,

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:51.870
registered him as white.

00:25:51.870 --> 00:25:57.370
And that adds that Lima had
presented himself as a writer.

00:25:57.370 --> 00:26:00.200
He says he's a writer.

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:03.040
That he wrote.

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:05.700
But Lima was not a loser at all.

00:26:05.700 --> 00:26:13.420
And then in 1911 he started
publishing Policarpo Quaresma

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:14.720
[speaking foreign language].

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:19.760
And then in 17 he published
this book, this as a book.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:23.210
The book is a story of a sort

00:26:23.210 --> 00:26:24.510
of Brazilian [speaking
foreign language].

00:26:24.510 --> 00:26:28.980
A critic of what he
called sheep [inaudible].

00:26:28.980 --> 00:26:33.470
In the book was well received,

00:26:33.470 --> 00:26:37.670
but not as well as
Lima had expected.

00:26:37.670 --> 00:26:42.200
So he wrote in his diary,
"Policarpo Quaresma,

00:26:42.200 --> 00:26:47.940
the idea that kills the
deception with pessimism."

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:52.310
By these days his life was
more than jumbled with those

00:26:52.310 --> 00:26:55.720
of his character --
of his characters.

00:26:55.720 --> 00:26:57.500
He was as Isaias Caminha

00:26:57.500 --> 00:26:59.440
and he was Gonzaga
Desa [assumed spelling]

00:26:59.440 --> 00:27:03.530
and the opposite was
nonetheless true.

00:27:03.530 --> 00:27:07.300
But the experience in the
hospital was really profound.

00:27:07.300 --> 00:27:11.790
He was a critical voice
against racial theories,

00:27:11.790 --> 00:27:14.830
like the ones right
-- that was written

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:17.570
by Nina Rodriguez
[assumed spelling],

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:20.800
that Nina Rodriguez
is a professor

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:23.310
of the faculty of
the [inaudible].

00:27:23.310 --> 00:27:31.890
That the defendant in Brazil,
was creates that generation.

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:35.090
He also was -- this
is the magazine

00:27:35.090 --> 00:27:39.860
of Nina Rodriguez called
Brazil Madico Magazine.

00:27:39.860 --> 00:27:45.590
And here you can see images
of some of the colleagues

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:49.240
of Lima Barreto in the hospital.

00:27:49.240 --> 00:27:55.750
Lima wrote a special diary about
his experience in the hospital

00:27:55.750 --> 00:28:00.440
and he used it to describe
the colleagues he had

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:05.270
in the hospital, saying, "In
the hospital all I can see

00:28:05.270 --> 00:28:06.570
is brown."

00:28:06.570 --> 00:28:12.100
And eventually he wrote,
"Constitution is not for us."

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:15.740
By the state of his life he
was really mixing everything.

00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:20.950
But life went on and Lima
kept looking to find a niche

00:28:20.950 --> 00:28:24.530
for himself in this
Republic of Letters.

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:29.570
In 1917 he was already
an anarchist

00:28:29.570 --> 00:28:34.330
and was emotionally caught
of the stripes of 17.

00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:37.600
He wrote article defending
the worker's class,

00:28:37.600 --> 00:28:40.610
the worker's right and
also defended a kind

00:28:40.610 --> 00:28:45.780
of military leader, very much
influenced by the context.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:50.500
He declares himself
with Dostoyevsky,

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:52.480
Balzac, Flobare, [inaudible].

00:28:52.480 --> 00:28:58.970
Lima defended as social
leader to very much connected

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:02.330
with the problems of his time.

00:29:02.330 --> 00:29:07.050
One has to recognize that Lima
Barreto was becoming really a

00:29:07.050 --> 00:29:09.970
public face of the republic.

00:29:09.970 --> 00:29:15.280
Then in 1919 another collapse.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:19.680
And there he was again
committed or "kidnapped"

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:22.410
as he put it, once again.

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:29.250
He was still a critic of racial
theories, but he was shaken

00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:34.120
to the point to recognize
certain signs of irratity.

00:29:34.120 --> 00:29:38.140
As an anarchist with a
[inaudible] for a mother

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:44.240
and a madman for a father,
he admitted, just once,

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:50.020
that he had signs of
degeneration to machination.

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:53.960
In this moment he wrote,
"Sometimes I'm afraid

00:29:53.960 --> 00:29:57.310
that my body is betraying me."

00:29:57.310 --> 00:30:01.060
At this time he looked
really tired.

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:05.380
There is one interesting point
that I want to stress to you.

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:12.960
In 1914 he was described
as a white person.

00:30:12.960 --> 00:30:20.320
In 1919, four years and a
half later, he was admitted

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:22.520
as a pardo [assumed spelling].

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:25.200
Pardo, this kind of color,

00:30:25.200 --> 00:30:29.330
that is almost impossible
to translate.

00:30:29.330 --> 00:30:32.380
It's a kind of etc.
of the senses.

00:30:32.380 --> 00:30:36.290
It's a kind of the none of
the others of the senses.

00:30:36.290 --> 00:30:39.830
Social color is the
term we use to talk

00:30:39.830 --> 00:30:44.620
about this way the Brazilians
negotiate with color.

00:30:44.620 --> 00:30:51.350
In a positive or sometimes
in a very negative agency.

00:30:51.350 --> 00:30:59.010
In his diary he often
wrote the names

00:30:59.010 --> 00:31:02.530
of his characters,
instead of his own.

00:31:02.530 --> 00:31:07.280
And in his novella his
own name, instead of those

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:11.010
of his character, only
to scratch it out again.

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:12.910
You can see in this document,

00:31:12.910 --> 00:31:17.530
you can see this is the
Cemittery of the Living.

00:31:17.530 --> 00:31:21.280
The last book Lima Barreto was
writing that he couldn't finish.

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:26.280
And I don't know if you
can see, he puts his name,

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:29.920
it's a long one, he puts his
name there, Lima Barreto,

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:34.490
and then he puts -- an opposite
thing is also true in his diary.

00:31:34.490 --> 00:31:36.020
Sometimes he puts the names

00:31:36.020 --> 00:31:40.020
of the fictional characters
instead of his own name.

00:31:40.020 --> 00:31:44.310
The thing is Lima Barreto was
really really fictionalizing

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:45.830
his life.

00:31:45.830 --> 00:31:52.330
We are now in 1922 and in this
year so important and symbolic

00:31:52.330 --> 00:31:55.440
to Brazil, Lima met
his own [inaudible].

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:59.340
He finished Clara dos Anjos.

00:31:59.340 --> 00:32:05.100
Which would be his most
suburban and feminist novel.

00:32:05.100 --> 00:32:08.060
Lima was working on this novel

00:32:08.060 --> 00:32:13.530
since he started
writing his diary, in 19.

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:16.990
At this time eventually
he started the diary,

00:32:16.990 --> 00:32:19.320
with a beautiful sentence.

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:23.510
He wrote, "When I started
writing this diary a

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:26.100
hope landed."

00:32:27.450 --> 00:32:33.900
Lima Barreto was a
writer with such a strong

00:32:33.900 --> 00:32:37.940
and powerful [inaudible]
but never married.

00:32:37.940 --> 00:32:43.060
Though he often dreamed of his
grandmother and his mother.

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:47.050
As for Clara dos Anjos, there
was many versions of this novel.

00:32:47.050 --> 00:32:51.870
The less of which they
had sprung to 1922

00:32:51.870 --> 00:32:57.060
and sees the dreamy
mulatto Clara dos Anjos,

00:32:57.060 --> 00:33:03.450
that we look pregnant,
alone, sad, very sad.

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:10.460
In 1921 Lima Barreto had already
retired from the war office

00:33:10.460 --> 00:33:12.730
and was working as a writer.

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:15.830
He counted the days, the hours,

00:33:15.830 --> 00:33:19.830
the minutes he lost
as a public servant.

00:33:19.830 --> 00:33:21.250
The last time he was seen

00:33:21.250 --> 00:33:23.460
in the [speaking foreign
language] de Janeiro he was

00:33:23.460 --> 00:33:24.970
covered in the celebrations

00:33:24.970 --> 00:33:28.920
around the Brazilian
Centenary of 1922.

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:31.890
Of which, of course,
he disapproved.

00:33:31.890 --> 00:33:36.680
He found it an example
of fake patriotism,

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:40.450
mixed with a nationalist
sentimentalist most Brazilians

00:33:40.450 --> 00:33:42.610
had from being [inaudible].

00:33:42.610 --> 00:33:46.880
The same year he
come into contact

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:50.430
with the publicists modernist.

00:33:50.430 --> 00:33:55.460
Whose magazine Klaxon he
received from the hands

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:56.840
of [speaking foreign language].

00:33:56.840 --> 00:33:58.970
The future very well,

00:33:58.970 --> 00:34:02.320
non-Brazilian historian,
and literary critic.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:06.350
He didn't like it at all.

00:34:06.350 --> 00:34:10.020
He thought it was
named after a horn,

00:34:10.020 --> 00:34:15.540
and a horn we call him a
car, which meant [inaudible]

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:21.130
and the code to the foreign.

00:34:21.130 --> 00:34:24.490
He [inaudible] it and
in return took a beating

00:34:24.490 --> 00:34:25.790
in the [inaudible] Klaxon.

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:31.040
This was the beginning of a
difficult future reception,

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:35.650
that consigned Lima Barreto
to the [inaudible] modernist.

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:39.090
Which was pretty
much no place at all.

00:34:39.090 --> 00:34:44.630
Something that never
was and never would be.

00:34:44.630 --> 00:34:46.930
To make matters worse
he was lumped

00:34:46.930 --> 00:34:49.990
into this category,
along with writers.

00:34:49.990 --> 00:34:55.780
He did not identify with them,
such as [inaudible] and worst

00:34:55.780 --> 00:34:57.080
of all [speaking
foreign language].

00:34:57.080 --> 00:35:04.800
But this kind of reception
would take its time.

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:08.470
We are now in November
22 and Lima Barreto,

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:10.690
who was always worried
he wouldn't be able

00:35:10.690 --> 00:35:14.230
to cover the cost of
his father's funeral,

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:17.900
died a day in a half
before his old man.

00:35:17.900 --> 00:35:22.890
With a copy of [speaking
foreign language], two words,

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:25.270
magazine, on his hands.

00:35:25.270 --> 00:35:29.980
Fitting enough for someone
who lived between two worlds.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:32.970
And so in neither at all.

00:35:32.970 --> 00:35:37.470
When he was in the suburbs
he missed the [inaudible].

00:35:37.470 --> 00:35:42.520
He disagreed with the Brazilian
Academy of Letter and tried

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:47.110
to enter the institution
three times, and failed.

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:51.450
Lima crafted the
characters of his books

00:35:51.450 --> 00:35:53.570
with an immense tenderness.

00:35:53.570 --> 00:35:58.430
They were rather different to
the ones the public was used to.

00:35:58.430 --> 00:36:03.750
There even religions mixed with
the prevailing catholisist.

00:36:03.750 --> 00:36:08.610
They were very skin toned,
and black and they lived

00:36:08.610 --> 00:36:11.870
on the outskirts of the
city, which resonated

00:36:11.870 --> 00:36:14.320
with the African [inaudible].

00:36:14.320 --> 00:36:17.080
And the short story called,
[speaking foreign language],

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:19.720
the Boy, for example,

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:24.790
Lima tenderly describes the
lands of his own neighbors.

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:26.090
[inaudible].

00:36:26.090 --> 00:36:28.790
Not far from there you
had the voodoo shacks

00:36:28.790 --> 00:36:31.660
and deposits of ancestral
beliefs.

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:36.130
They go and mixing African
religions with spirits.

00:36:36.130 --> 00:36:39.740
They spread like wildfire.

00:36:39.740 --> 00:36:44.180
The Catholic Church does not
satisfy our humble people.

00:36:44.180 --> 00:36:48.180
the priest fought most of our
people can't really communicate

00:36:48.180 --> 00:36:53.110
with the divine, but the medium,
the warlock, the witch doctor,

00:36:53.110 --> 00:36:56.490
if they don't deceive
divinity in their trances they

00:36:56.490 --> 00:37:01.100
at least receive spirits and
souls, which being no longer

00:37:01.100 --> 00:37:07.100
of this world are closer to god
and therefore partake a little

00:37:07.100 --> 00:37:09.920
of his eternal and
immense wisdom.

00:37:15.130 --> 00:37:18.110
He also liked to see
himself as a rebel.

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:20.180
On principle for fun

00:37:20.180 --> 00:37:23.750
and to irritate [speaking
foreign language].

00:37:23.750 --> 00:37:29.210
Oh, this is the --
this is the retake

00:37:29.210 --> 00:37:30.510
of [speaking foreign language].

00:37:30.510 --> 00:37:32.600
He was against pompous
politicians,

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:37.430
against the new aristocracy and
against cosmetic journalist,

00:37:37.430 --> 00:37:41.670
against [inaudible] literature,
against [inaudible] and so,

00:37:41.670 --> 00:37:47.410
he suddenly railed against
metropolis [speaking foreign

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:48.710
language] and [inaudible].

00:37:48.710 --> 00:37:52.310
He denounced the abuse of
society committed against women,

00:37:52.310 --> 00:37:58.040
but accused feminism of being
a sheep importation in Brazil.

00:37:58.040 --> 00:38:00.090
He defended simple habits,

00:38:00.090 --> 00:38:04.900
but disliked soccer,
Zumba and Carnival.

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:08.540
He detests civil servants,
yet learned his living

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:09.840
as a war office [inaudible].

00:38:09.840 --> 00:38:14.100
Despised his deplorable
handwriting,

00:38:14.100 --> 00:38:18.070
he had a terrible
handwriting for a clerk.

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:22.420
In fact, in [speaking foreign
language] the life and death

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:28.380
of [speaking foreign language]
published in 1918 on the pretext

00:38:28.380 --> 00:38:32.870
of summarize the works of
his department, Lima embarked

00:38:32.870 --> 00:38:38.240
on a hilarious reflection on the
job he did for so many years.

00:38:38.240 --> 00:38:43.140
On my first day at the war
office I realized very clearly

00:38:43.140 --> 00:38:46.450
that we are all born
for the civil service.

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:52.740
So, same as less was my adaption
that I felt as though I had come

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:55.390
into this world for
no other reason

00:38:55.390 --> 00:38:59.840
than to put my limited
grammar and office [inaudible]

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:03.210
to the service of the
state and its mission

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:07.390
to regulate the march
of the nation.

00:39:07.390 --> 00:39:11.080
Basically that was Lima
Barreto in a nutshell.

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:16.310
For a full of contradiction,
full of his own subjectivities,

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:23.090
but with very firm notions,
theories, thesis, idiosyncrasies

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:26.500
and pains and dreams
and products.

00:39:26.500 --> 00:39:31.010
Lima didn't' experience
slavery at very close quarters,

00:39:31.010 --> 00:39:33.390
not like his two grandmothers.

00:39:33.390 --> 00:39:36.330
It was at asylum that he learned

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:39.190
from his fellow inmates
the importance

00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:43.100
of understanding what
he called his origins.

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:45.390
[speaking foreign
language] who used

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:50.350
to call Lima [speaking foreign
language] had made some money

00:39:50.350 --> 00:39:53.600
selling his master's
groceries at the market.

00:39:53.600 --> 00:39:57.000
And when the time was
right he uses his savings

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.080
to buy his freedom.

00:39:59.080 --> 00:40:02.790
Sometime later he fell in
love with Maria Pollina

00:40:02.790 --> 00:40:05.200
and bought her freedom too.

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:09.430
They moved in together and
all was going swimmingly

00:40:09.430 --> 00:40:12.750
until she left him.

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:14.620
Then came his [inaudible].

00:40:14.620 --> 00:40:20.690
That was the state [inaudible]
was in when he met the author.

00:40:20.690 --> 00:40:25.950
As Lima tell us, [inaudible] was
quite a figure and he writes,

00:40:25.950 --> 00:40:29.920
"Many other facts of this
kind pass between us,

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:34.420
and now that this pair
besets me, I can recall --

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:39.030
I can't recall that unique
black fellow without thinking

00:40:39.030 --> 00:40:41.860
that what gives life
its charm more

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:45.180
than anything else is
the candle of the simple

00:40:45.180 --> 00:40:48.630
and the resignation
of the hammer."

00:40:48.630 --> 00:40:53.250
In his self-styled militant
autobiographical literature Lima

00:40:53.250 --> 00:40:57.700
ended becoming and living
out his own characters.

00:40:57.700 --> 00:41:02.110
He was each of them in turn
and all of them at once.

00:41:02.110 --> 00:41:05.210
And also none of them at all.

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:07.100
Lima was in a hurry.

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:09.580
His literature, he
was in a hurry.

00:41:09.580 --> 00:41:12.600
Of course, he had no way of
knowing that he would die

00:41:12.600 --> 00:41:18.220
at the age of 41 from an
alcoholic induced heart attack.

00:41:18.220 --> 00:41:19.580
Life was short.

00:41:19.580 --> 00:41:22.820
His literature will live longer.

00:41:22.820 --> 00:41:25.840
He was an author who, as
the critic used it to say,

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:28.410
confessed the whole time.

00:41:28.410 --> 00:41:31.100
But he did much more than that.

00:41:31.100 --> 00:41:34.550
He was a man of his time,
the sort that becomes

00:41:34.550 --> 00:41:39.780
at once a witness to an activist
of the period in which he lived.

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:43.500
A writer who wrote with
feeling and with soul.

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:47.010
Feeling the creative
sense of perfect.

00:41:47.010 --> 00:41:50.180
It's impossible to read Lima
Barreto without being affected

00:41:50.180 --> 00:41:56.020
by him, without being swept
up on his own magical carpet.

00:41:56.020 --> 00:42:00.730
Blurring the most of his borders
between fiction and non-fiction,

00:42:00.730 --> 00:42:05.780
Lima Barreto showed us
another visual or another side

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:08.420
to the one we know very well.

00:42:08.420 --> 00:42:10.380
The Brazil of the big hearted

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.050
as Manuel [speaking
foreign language].

00:42:12.050 --> 00:42:16.550
Sharing on its shoulders a
word of pain, but which refuses

00:42:16.550 --> 00:42:18.920
to take it lying down.

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:23.920
On the contrary, of Brazil,
let's stand up and fight.

00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:30.120
T he republic he watch less
was not the one he dreamt

00:42:30.120 --> 00:42:32.440
and -- sorry, dreamt of.

00:42:32.440 --> 00:42:37.470
It became in its own
way [inaudible] racist,

00:42:37.470 --> 00:42:42.220
all toward looking in,
above all, deeply unjust.

00:42:42.220 --> 00:42:44.090
[speaking foreign
language] once wrote

00:42:44.090 --> 00:42:46.310
that the best witnesses
are those

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:49.680
who stay behind to
tell the tale.

00:42:49.680 --> 00:42:52.710
More specifically those
who bring the past

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:55.230
into the present and vice versa.

00:42:55.230 --> 00:42:58.940
In the case of Lima Barreto
all similarity is not

00:42:58.940 --> 00:43:02.110
mere coincidence.

00:43:02.110 --> 00:43:04.630
But before I finish
this presentation,

00:43:04.630 --> 00:43:08.380
let me also conclude how
Lima Barreto continued

00:43:08.380 --> 00:43:15.270
to be very contemporary,
even after almost 100 year.

00:43:15.270 --> 00:43:21.580
Brazil -- in fact, Brazil
cannot blame it all on the past,

00:43:21.580 --> 00:43:27.240
but Brazil is still a sample
[inaudible] social inequality

00:43:27.240 --> 00:43:30.470
and practice of structural
racism.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:33.600
Poor people, especially
in Tibet, black poor,

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:37.340
are far more likely to be
condemned in the courts

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:40.680
than to die younger,
have more limited access

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:44.110
to public higher education,
and are far less likely

00:43:44.110 --> 00:43:46.910
to hold executive positions.

00:43:52.100 --> 00:43:55.640
I don't want to bother
you with numbers,

00:43:55.640 --> 00:43:58.200
but let me introduce
a few of them.

00:43:58.200 --> 00:43:59.620
A few examples.

00:43:59.620 --> 00:44:04.200
Why there has been a general
uptake in life expectancy

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:05.960
in Brazilian population,

00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:09.480
the increase has not been
equal across the board.

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:13.180
High mortality rates
caused by urban violence,

00:44:13.180 --> 00:44:15.110
among the male population,

00:44:15.110 --> 00:44:17.910
particularly the young
black population,

00:44:17.910 --> 00:44:20.270
and precarious access
to medical treatment

00:44:20.270 --> 00:44:24.340
and healthcare have
both taken their too.

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:30.050
In general, 92% of the
victims of [inaudible] violence

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:33.160
in Brazil were young and male.

00:44:33.160 --> 00:44:36.680
Moreover, if you take the
population as a whole,

00:44:36.680 --> 00:44:39.850
the black youth is by
far the most likely

00:44:39.850 --> 00:44:41.870
to die a violent death.

00:44:41.870 --> 00:44:48.560
While in 2012 the murder rate
among the white youth was 29%

00:44:48.560 --> 00:44:51.540
per 1000 inhabitants.

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:55.650
Practically same as
to the population.

00:44:55.650 --> 00:45:00.270
The figure for black
youth was 82%.

00:45:00.270 --> 00:45:01.570
It's not just a matter

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:04.880
of comparing per
capita death rates.

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:08.500
There is a very giant gulf
between these two groups

00:45:08.500 --> 00:45:11.960
when it comes to assessing
the risk of murder.

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:18.170
Today a young black man in
Brazil is 2.5 times more likely

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:21.300
to be killed than
a young white man.

00:45:21.300 --> 00:45:25.540
In the northeast of the
country, where murder rates tend

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:28.570
to be higher, the
difference is doubled.

00:45:28.570 --> 00:45:31.880
A young black man
in the northeast

00:45:31.880 --> 00:45:36.210
of Brazil is 5 times more likely
to be murdered than a white man

00:45:36.210 --> 00:45:39.200
of the same age in
the same state.

00:45:39.200 --> 00:45:42.260
Translated into absolute
figures,

00:45:42.260 --> 00:45:48.220
what we see over 56,000
murders per year in Brazil.

00:45:48.220 --> 00:45:51.500
30,000 of those kids
are youth ages

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:55.200
between 15 and 29 years old.

00:45:55.200 --> 00:45:58.950
And 75% of those are black.

00:45:58.950 --> 00:46:03.300
So we have a very
specific color and age bias

00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:05.670
in annual murders rates.

00:46:05.670 --> 00:46:10.570
And it's sadly in line with the
nation historical inequality.

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:15.930
The data also leaves no
doubt as to the vulnerability

00:46:15.930 --> 00:46:21.390
and limited access to rise among
this part of the population.

00:46:21.390 --> 00:46:24.450
Let me move on -- if I
would move to literacies,

00:46:24.450 --> 00:46:26.850
I could give other data.

00:46:26.850 --> 00:46:33.000
If I would go to racial
inequality in schools,

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:38.590
I will prove you
that race is a plus.

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:42.360
If we talk about what we
consider extremely poor

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:47.580
in Brazil, once again
inequality is considerable here.

00:46:47.580 --> 00:46:51.050
7.2 of the black
population classifies

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:56.380
as extremely poor,
against 3% of whites.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:47:00.510
What we see here is one of
many examples of continuity

00:47:00.510 --> 00:47:03.180
between the slave owned past,

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:07.510
then post-evolution
period and the present.

00:47:07.510 --> 00:47:11.450
I could talk about access to
public and private healthcare,

00:47:11.450 --> 00:47:15.760
pencil and benefit systems,
position in job markets,

00:47:15.760 --> 00:47:20.310
formal and informal
employment, domestic labor.

00:47:20.310 --> 00:47:23.970
Inequality is too
real in Brazil.

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:34.390
In sum, in work,
birth, death, health,

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:37.480
race is always a kind of plus.

00:47:37.480 --> 00:47:41.730
Data goes above --
underlies the reality

00:47:41.730 --> 00:47:45.010
of discrimination
and racism in Brazil.

00:47:45.010 --> 00:47:48.880
It points to urgent
demands for policies

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:52.150
to promote greater racial
equality as [inaudible],

00:47:52.150 --> 00:47:57.400
use it to ask for in the
beginning of the 20th century.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:48:02.450
A country more inclusive,
plural, a real democracy,

00:48:02.450 --> 00:48:08.280
and not a republic, as Lima
Barreto used to ask for in 1922.

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:10.080
Thank you very much.

