01:21:59.840 --> 01:22:04.080
So, you can smile all this
and can think it's a joke.

01:22:04.080 --> 01:22:06.050
It's not a joke.

01:22:06.050 --> 01:22:07.350
It's not a joke.

01:22:07.350 --> 01:22:11.190
It's the same story we are
reading here in Lima Barreto,

01:22:11.190 --> 01:22:14.420
that the first time he
was described as white,

01:22:14.420 --> 01:22:18.950
because he was a writer,
because he was a public servant.

01:22:18.950 --> 01:22:22.630
And the second time he was a
[speaking foreign language],

01:22:22.630 --> 01:22:25.500
because he was [inaudible],
he was tired.

01:22:25.500 --> 01:22:29.850
You know? So, this is the
way people use color, by --

01:22:29.850 --> 01:22:35.940
but in my opinion, I have a lot
of colleagues here that can talk

01:22:35.940 --> 01:22:40.450
and agree or disagree with me,
things are changing in Brazil.

01:22:40.450 --> 01:22:46.700
Now you can talk about
having black proud.

01:22:46.700 --> 01:22:50.880
You can talk about different
origins, you can talk

01:22:50.880 --> 01:22:54.080
about different Africans
in Brazil.

01:22:54.080 --> 01:22:58.090
So, in my opinion things
are really changing.

01:22:58.090 --> 01:23:04.100
And it's not so easy to say,
"No, we do not have this kind

01:23:04.100 --> 01:23:09.160
of thing, or this kind
of thing of racist."

01:23:09.160 --> 01:23:13.200
But at the same time when
I wrote that book, "Brazil,

01:23:13.200 --> 01:23:16.160
a Biography," together
with Heloisa,

01:23:16.160 --> 01:23:19.420
we said we historians
we like to say

01:23:19.420 --> 01:23:23.380
that history is a
game of changing.

01:23:23.380 --> 01:23:26.880
But history can be
a very stubborn way

01:23:26.880 --> 01:23:28.850
of repeating things.

01:23:28.850 --> 01:23:33.980
So, in 1988 at Universe of Sao
Paulo we finished our research

01:23:33.980 --> 01:23:38.840
that we asked Brazilians
about racial discrimination.

01:23:38.840 --> 01:23:41.570
And it was very simple,
we asked Brazilians,

01:23:41.570 --> 01:23:46.260
the first question
was, "Do you have --

01:23:46.260 --> 01:23:49.250
do you feel discrimination now?"

01:23:49.250 --> 01:23:53.660
96% of the answers were no.

01:23:53.660 --> 01:23:55.990
The second question was,
"Do you know a person

01:23:55.990 --> 01:23:59.860
that felt -- was discriminated?"

01:23:59.860 --> 01:24:03.720
And 99% of the answers were yes.

01:24:03.720 --> 01:24:06.360
And the third, "if you said yes,

01:24:06.360 --> 01:24:09.350
try to describe the
relationship you have."

01:24:09.350 --> 01:24:12.970
And people used to say things
like this, "My neighbor,

01:24:12.970 --> 01:24:17.040
my grandmother, my
brother, my boyfriend."

01:24:17.040 --> 01:24:19.370
So, the formal conclusion was

01:24:19.370 --> 01:24:21.830
that every Brazilian thinks
he's an island of race

01:24:21.830 --> 01:24:25.420
or democracy surrounded
by races everywhere.

01:24:25.420 --> 01:24:26.720
But the surprise is

01:24:26.720 --> 01:24:31.580
that [inaudible] magazine
just finished a new research

01:24:31.580 --> 01:24:35.360
and again you can see this
kind of thing, you know.

01:24:35.360 --> 01:24:40.060
We had this public face.

01:24:40.060 --> 01:24:45.430
As an anthropologist and I'm a
very much a [inaudible] person,

01:24:45.430 --> 01:24:49.780
no, I think that myth
it's not something

01:24:49.780 --> 01:24:52.100
that -- it's not alive.

01:24:52.100 --> 01:24:56.400
Myth, the structure of
the myths is that --

01:24:56.400 --> 01:25:00.840
the myth tells you not
the truth, but tells you

01:25:00.840 --> 01:25:04.100
about contradictions
of this society.

01:25:04.100 --> 01:25:08.130
So we have this very base root
myth of race of democracy.

01:25:08.130 --> 01:25:14.490
The problem is, it's not
a lie, it's not a lie,

01:25:14.490 --> 01:25:17.590
because it's a public
representation.

01:25:17.590 --> 01:25:22.910
It's something very private
that he people want to believe.

01:25:22.910 --> 01:25:29.690
And why affirmative action is
so important in our quota system

01:25:29.690 --> 01:25:31.990
and it's so important
in our country,

01:25:31.990 --> 01:25:35.440
because we have to
talk about this.

01:25:35.440 --> 01:25:39.370
The worse place to
live is invisibility.

01:25:39.370 --> 01:25:44.070
And in Brazil this idea of
playing with colors has a color

01:25:44.070 --> 01:25:48.080
of invisibility, has the color
of [speaking foreign language].

